In .NET 10, Android's `adjustResize` is fully deprecated and MAUI adopted edge-to-edge display. The replacement is to react to **window insets** so your layout adjusts when the IME (keyboard) appears.

**Recommended approach — listen to IME insets on Android:**

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
}

class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // The bottom padding = keyboard height minus nav bar (already accounted for)
        int bottomPadding = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom - navInsets.Bottom, 0);

        v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottomPadding);

        return ViewCompat.OnApplyWindowInsets(v, insets);
    }
}
```

**Simpler cross-platform alternative — use a `Grid` with keyboard-aware margin:**

If you prefer a XAML-only approach, wrap your input in a layout and use the **CommunityToolkit `KeyboardBehavior`** (available for .NET 10), or structure your page like:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ... />

    <Entry Grid.Row="1"
           Placeholder="Type a message..."
           x:Name="MessageEntry" />
</Grid>
```

Then in your page code-behind, subscribe to keyboard changes:

```csharp
#if ANDROID
Microsoft.Maui.ApplicationModel.Platform.CurrentActivity!
    .Window!.SetSoftInputMode(Android.Views.SoftInput.AdjustNothing);
#endif
```

Combined with the insets listener above, this gives you full control.

**Key takeaway:** Replace `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` with `ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener` and manually set bottom padding based on `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()`. This is the Android-blessed approach going forward.
